<h2 id="IDQuickReference">Quick Reference for Reporting</h2>
<p>Use this list as a reminder of the primary steps for using this site and the corresponding locations for completing certain related actions.</p>

<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/OrderOfOperations.jpg")" alt="Order of Operations" /></p>

<h3 id="create-an-online-user-account">1.  Create an Online User Account</h3>
<p>This account should remain unique to you, and will be used to access information about your properties or ones for which you are reporting.</p>

<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/SignUp.jpg")" alt="Creating an Account" /></p>

<p>Each time you return, you&rsquo;ll simply log in with the <strong>&ldquo;Login&rdquo;</strong> button, using your previously entered e-mail address and password.  You also reset your forgotten password here.</p>

<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/Login.jpg")" alt="Logging In" /></p>

<h3 id="update-and-maintain-your-user-account--properties">2.  Update and Maintain your User Account</h3>

<p>Once you are logged in you will see a button for managing your account. On the My Account page, you can a. manage your own contact information, b. change your password, c. change your e-mail address.

</p>

<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/MyAccountPage_UserInfo.jpg")" alt="My Account" /></p>

<h3 id="map-the-contiguous-acres">3. Map the Contiguous Acres</h3>
<p>You will draw an area on the map representing each distinct contiguous acreage polygon.  You can access the map using the <strong>&ldquo;Reporting&rdquo;</strong> tab on the main page.</p>

<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/Reporting.jpg")" alt="Reporting Information Using the Map" /></p>

<p>1)  Zoom to your area of interest, and click the &ldquo;Map a Contiguous Area&rdquo; icon to activate the tool<br />
 2)  Indicate the reason you are adding this contiguous area - such as it is a new area, or a modification to an existing one; click proceed<br />
 3)  Click the &ldquo;Proposed Contiguous Acres&rdquo; layer to activate it (it will turn black when activated), and click on the map to start drawing.</p>

<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/MapACA_Start.jpg")" alt="Add Contiguous Acreage boundary to the Map" /></p>

<p>4)  Add a name to distinguish this area from others.<br />
 5)  Click OK, acknowledging that your proposed boundary has been submitted, and that you can return later to confirm the actual boundary as approved by HPWD.</p>

<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/MapACA_NameIt.jpg")" alt="Add Contiguous Acreage &quot;name&quot; or description" /></p>

<h3 id="map-the-meters-or-alternate-metering-methods">4. Map the Meter(s) or Alternate Metering Method(s)</h3>
<p>Map the point location where water production will be measured for each of your properties.  The main HPWD web page has detailed instructions on <a href="http://hpwd.com/meter-forms/">metering and alternative methods for reporting production</a>.</p>

<p>1)  Activate the <strong>&ldquo;Map Meter&rdquo;</strong> tool.<br />
 2)  Click on the proposed meters layer in the tool, and click the map to indicate the meter location.<br />
 3) Enter the characteristics of your meter or alternate measurement method, including a start reading. Note that the installation date and the start reading date may be different.
<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/MapUpdateMeterAttributes.jpg")" alt="Update meter information" /></p>

<h3 id="associate-wells-to-a-meter">5. Associate Wells to A Meter</h3>
<p>All the wells within a contiguous acreage must be metered.  Well-to-meter associations can be entered and reviewed on the map and in the &ldquo;Reporting Summary&rdquo; page.</p>

<p>1)  Activate the <strong>&ldquo;Associate a Meter with Wells&rdquo;</strong> tool<br />
 2)  Select a distance to search around your meter for nearby wells.<br />
 3)  Click on the meter, and select those well permit numbers that should be associated with the meter.  Repeat for every meter and/or well associated with your contiguous acreages. Red lines will appear that signify a well-to-meter association.</p>

<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/Meter-To-Well-Assoc.jpg")" alt="Assciate Wells to Meters" /></p>

<p>4) The option to show all meter-well associations leaves the lines between wells and meters visible, to aid in researching existing or missing associations.</p>

<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/Meter-To-Well-Show.jpg")" alt="Show Meter-to-Well Associations" /></p>

<h4 id="reporting-a-missing-well">Reporting a Missing Well</h4>
<p>If you find that a permitted well is missing from the map altogether, HPWD would appreciate if you identify the location of the missing well so that it can be researched.  REMEMBER:  This tool is not part of the well permitting process, and any wells that are not yet permitted must go through the official process with that department of the HPWD.  Further, if you find a well that is mapped, but in the wrong location, please contact HPWD directly to have the well location re-mapped instead of adding another point with this tool.</p>

<p>1)  Click on the <strong>&ldquo;Identify Missing Wells&rdquo;</strong> icon to activate the tool<br />
2)  Select the Missing Wells layer to activate the tool<br />
3)  Click the map to add a point where the well should be located<br />
4)  Review and confirm that the contact information for the person who can verify the missing well information.</p>

<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/IdentifyMissingWell.jpg")" alt="Identify a Missing Well" /></p>

<h3 id="report-production-readings">6. Record Production Readings</h3>
<p>An end meter reading needs to be entered at least once each year in order to calculate actual production as compared to what is allowed for each contiguous area.  </p>

<p>1)  Activate the <strong>&ldquo;Record a Meter Reading&rdquo;</strong> tool<br />
 2)  Click on the meter and enter values into the pop-up window.  Click OK.  If you enter more than one interim end-reading, the most recent three values will show in the pop-up.</p>

<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/ReportProduction.jpg")" alt="Report Production Readings" /></p>

<p>Interim readings can be entered for any meter at any time as a tool for checking the status of your current production rate.  The &ldquo;Annual Report&rdquo; tab can then be used to summarize the values entered to-date relative to each contiguous acreage.</p>

<h3 id="associate-properties-to-account">7. Manually Associate Properties to your Account</h3>
<p>As you enter information for reporting, such as a meter or contiguous acreage polygon, the underlying properties are associated to your user account as well. In 2012, this method is being used to manage what information is visible to each user. </p>

<p>In most cases for reporting year 2012, this information should be left as is (as it is assigned automatically by the mapping tools). </p>

<p>However, if you own some property for which someone else is reporting on your behalf, you may want to see what they are reporting. In that case, you will use the links provided at the bottom of the My Account page to associate a property to your account manually.
</p>

<p><img src="@Url.Image("help/MyAccountPage_AddProperties.jpg")" alt="Property Descriptions" /></p>

<p>Each of these links will allow you select a property, either by typing an ownername (as on file at the County Appraisal District) or by pointing to the desired location on the map. Once a property is on this list, you will see features that have been added to the map by yourself or others that are related to this property.</p>

