<h2 id="IDBackgroundInfo">Background Information</h2>
<p>This web page is being provided to assist water producers in maintaining compliance with the <a href="http://www.hpwd.com/Downloads/FINAL%20District%20Rules%20As%20Amended%20July%2019,%202011/Amended%20HPWD%20Rules%20Adopted%207-19-2011.pdf">&ldquo;Rules of the High Plains Underground Water Conservation District No. 1&rdquo;</a>.  </p>

<p>This site has been developed in stages to provide interim capabilities to the public during development. Users were initially provided the ability to locate and enter data associated with a meter installation and the land ownership tied to the water production. Additional functionality for drawing contiguous acreages and identifying missing wells was added. Finally, the annual reporting summary was added. Most recently, the application has been updated to de-emphasize the associated land ownership information and focus on the online user (the one doing the reporting) taking primary responsibility for whatever features they add. The server infrastructure has also been updated to accommodate the increased use of the online tools by the water user community.</p>

<h3 id="IDInfoProperty">Reporting Water Use by Property</h3>
<p>As specified in the Rule, the Owner of a property is responsible for measuring all the water production from that property, regardless of the water&rsquo;s point of use.  </p>

<p>This site allows persons other than the Owner to report on a property, but every online user account must be associated to at least one property/Owner before adding a meter. </p>

<p>The basis of this property to owner association is the Appraisal District roll information from each county. It is common to for the same property owner to be listed as John Doe, John and Mary Doe, or John Doe Trust in the Appraisal District records. Because the property is officially recorded that way, it can sometimes be difficult to find the correct owner name in a list, and to correctly associate the property (correct section or labor) being reported. </p>

<p>Though this process may seem somewhat cumbersome, it was originally deemed important for maintaining the integrity of the information being reported throughout the District.</p>

<p>However, given recent feedback that the appraisal district information is too out of date to be dependable, this explicit property/Owner association may be removed from the user interface for the 2013 reporting year.</p>

<h3 id="IDInfoAccuracy">Data Accuracy</h3>
<p>HPWD is using data from each County Appraisal District (CAD) to provide the most accurate information regarding current land ownership. However, because this tool does not connect to the CAD’s directly, there may be instances where users will need to update the information in this tool to match what is known to be currently accurate.  </p>

<p>Well locations are approximate for all wells drilled prior to 2004 because the district did not measure each well site prior to 2004. The well may not be in the exact location of the physical well site. You are encouraged to contact HPWD directly if you find a well that is on the map in the wrong location.  </p>

<p>Other data in the map represents a collection of information from different data sources, and each source has different data accuracy requirements.  High Plains is grateful to have access to these sources of information and asks that users be mindful that features are presented for context and may not align exactly to each other.  <strong>Information added by users of the High Plains system should aim to align with the map imagery instead of other map features</strong> (such as roads, ownership boundaries, or legals).</p>

<h3 id="IDInfoSiteBenefits">Benefits of this Site versus Paper</h3>
<p>You can choose to submit all your information using <a href="http://hpwd.com/Downloads/Meter%20forms/Revised%20Meter%20Registration%20Form%20(10-24-11).pdf">paper forms</a> but you are encouraged to use this online tool instead.    By creating an online account, you will<br />
    a.  see information about your properties (those you are authorized to see) as it is represented in the HPWD database<br />
    b.  be able to, at any time, review the status of your actual production as compared to your allowable production and banked water balance<br />
    c.  Have access to maps of your property with the latest NAIP imagery.</p>

<p>Remember, if you are uncomfortable with using the online system, you can call or go in to the HPWD office and have someone help you setup your online account.  </p>

<h3 id="IDInfoMeterProcess">Outline of Online Meter Reporting Process</h3>
<p>The order of completion, no matter when in the year you begin the process, remains the same.  It is recommended at this time that you complete the online reporting steps in the order listed below.  </p>

<ul>
  <li>Create User Account.  </li>
  <li>Draw boundaries around your contiguous acreage. These boundaries will be reviewed by the HPWD for accuracy and completeness.  </li>
  <li>Map the location of your meter or alternate metering method, including characteristics of the meter such as the start reading.  </li>
  <li>Associate the wells within each contiguous area to a meter.  </li>
  <li>Update the information for each meter to include at least one end reading at the end of the production year, to be read between Dec 15 - Jan 15.</li>
  <li>Confirm the production rates reported are accurate and submit a summary report for all of your contiguous acreage.  </li>
</ul>

