<h3 id="IDFAQReporting">Reporting your Information</h3>
<p><strong><em>I can&rsquo;t find my well.</em></strong><br />
<p>If you are looking for a well that has not yet been permitted through the HPWD, it will not show on the map. In this case, you can add a metering location to the map for production reporting purposes, BUT you must wait to complete the permit application process with HPWD before associating the meter to the well.</p>

<p><strong><em>My meter was installed prior to the rulemaking.  How do I enter my grandfathered meter?</em></strong>
Grandfathered meters are entered the same way as new meters. When you get to the Edit Meter form in the map, you will type your meter information in text boxes labeled just for grandfathered meters (instead of picking your meter model from the list of approved meters).</p>

<p><strong><em>I&rsquo;ve found my property and my wells, but they aren&rsquo;t in the correct location.  Do I put my meter on top of the well as it is mapped, or where it ought to be as I see it in the image?</em></strong><br />
Many of the features in the map may not have been mapped as accurately as the image background.  If you are adding a new meter (or alternate metering method), please position it exactly where you think it is relative to the image, not the other features on the map such as wells and property lines.</p>

<p><strong><em>I entered a meter location previously, but now realize it is in the wrong location.  I see the meter on the map but I can no longer edit or delete it.  How do I update my information?</em></strong><br />
Meter locations and attributes remain editable by users as &ldquo;proposed&rdquo; features until they have been reviewed by the High Plains Water District, at which point they become &ldquo;confirmed&rdquo; features.  If you can no longer edit your meter online, you&rsquo;ll need to contact the HPWD (<a href="&#109;&#097;&#105;&#108;&#116;&#111;:&#104;&#101;&#108;&#112;&#064;&#104;&#112;&#119;&#100;&#046;&#099;&#111;&#109;" title="e-mail HPWD for help">&#104;&#101;&#108;&#112;&#064;&#104;&#112;&#119;&#100;&#046;&#099;&#111;&#109;</a>) to determine how to update the information.</p>

<p><strong><em>My map doesn&rsquo;t look like the one in the video. Is something wrong?</em></strong> 
No.  Because this site is constantly being improved, the videos may use a different map or be missing some of the mapping tools that have recently been added.  The information in the video should still be accurate, or the video will be updated.</p>

